post_cb({"6414247": {"ParentId": "6414030", "CommentCount": "2", "Body": "<p>I believe behavior is well-defined because of <strong>8[dcl.decl]/3</strong></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_6414030_6414247_0\">Each init-declarator in a declaration is analyzed separately as if it was in a declaration by itself.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Which is even additionally explained in a footnote as</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_6414030_6414247_1\">A declaration with several declarators is usually equivalent to the corresponding sequence of declarations each with a single\n  declarator. That is</p>\n<pre><code>T D1, D2, ... Dn;\n</code></pre>\n<p id=\"so_6414030_6414247_2\">is usually equvalent to</p>\n<pre><code>T D1; T D2; ... T Dn;\n</code></pre>\n</blockquote>\n", "OwnerUserId": "273767", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "6414247", "Score": "20", "CreationDate": "2011-06-20T16:11:12.687", "LastActivityDate": "2011-06-20T16:11:12.687"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_6414030_6414247_0": {"section_id": 3196, "quality": 1.0, "length": 8}, "so_6414030_6414247_1": {"section_id": 3196, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}, "n3337": {"so_6414030_6414247_0": {"section_id": 3070, "quality": 1.0, "length": 8}, "so_6414030_6414247_1": {"section_id": 3070, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}, "n4659": {"so_6414030_6414247_0": {"section_id": 3958, "quality": 1.0, "length": 8}, "so_6414030_6414247_1": {"section_id": 3958, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}}, "6414206": {"ParentId": "6414030", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>As you suspect there is a sequence point after each initializer expression, because they're full expressions (1.9/16, 1.9/12).</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "212870", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "6414206", "Score": "8", "CreationDate": "2011-06-20T16:07:46.183", "LastActivityDate": "2011-06-20T16:07:46.183"}, "6414030": {"CommentCount": "5", "AcceptedAnswerId": "6414247", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "1561378", "CreationDate": "2011-06-20T15:55:31.593", "LastActivityDate": "2012-10-04T15:18:48.420", "LastEditDate": "2012-10-04T15:18:48.420", "ViewCount": "1088", "FavoriteCount": "4", "Title": "Is the comma in a variable list a sequence point?", "Id": "6414030", "Score": "20", "Body": "<p>In the following type of code is there a sequence point between each variable construction, or is the result undefined?</p>\n<pre><code>int a = 0;\nint b = a++, c = a++;\n</code></pre>\n<p>I wasn't able to find in the standard a specific reference to a sequence point here. Does that mean it is undefined, or just that I failed in my search? The completion of an expression is a sequence point, but does the above initialization also count?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><variables><comma><sequence-points>", "OwnerUserId": "229686", "AnswerCount": "2"}});